{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489075"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"583"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/583"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.83,0.05,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/583"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67822"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"912"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28279"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of dyspnoea, chest pain, headache, and light-headedness. His symptoms worsen when leaning forward. He has a 65 pack-year smoking history but no other significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is marked facial plethora and oedema with prominent venous distension in the neck. Cardiovascular examination reveals dual heart sounds with no murmurs. Respiratory examination reveals normal breath sounds throughout with no added sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral pericarditis","Superior vena cava syndrome","Cardiac tamponade","Pulmonary embolism","Atypical pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior vena cava syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, including facial plethora, neck vein distension, and symptoms that worsen with forward flexion. The extensive smoking history strongly suggests an underlying bronchogenic carcinoma as the cause, which is the most common aetiology of SVC syndrome in adults. The syndrome occurs when the SVC is compressed or invaded by disease processes in the upper thorax, leading to impaired venous drainage from the head, neck, and upper extremities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral pericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with pleuritic chest pain that improves with sitting forward (unlike this patient\u0027s symptoms which worsen). While it can cause dyspnoea, it would not explain the facial plethora and neck vein distension. A pericardial friction rub would often be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac tamponade\u003C/strong\u003E presents with Beck\u0027s triad (hypotension, elevated JVP, muffled heart sounds) and pulsus paradoxus. This patient is haemodynamically stable with clear heart sounds, making tamponade unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute onset dyspnoea, pleuritic chest pain, and tachycardia. While it can cause elevated JVP, it would not explain the facial plethora and oedema seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the facial plethora or neck vein distension. While it can cause dyspnoea and chest pain, patients typically have constitutional symptoms and some abnormal respiratory examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Superior vena cava syndrome commonly presents with facial plethora, neck vein distension, and symptoms that worsen with forward flexion.","Lung cancer is the most common cause of superior vena cava syndrome in adults.","The diagnosis of superior vena cava syndrome is primarily clinical, based on characteristic physical findings."],"references":["Zimmerman S, Davis M. Rapid Fire: Superior Vena Cava Syndrome. Emerg Clin N Am. 2018; 36:577-84."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67822"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"583"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67822"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T19:55:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T19:59:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"583"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi